:::summary
Poetry is the oldest and most elevated form of literary art — language shaped by rhythm, sound, image, and compression into something that reaches places plain prose cannot. From the Psalms of David to [Homer](article.html?id=homer)'s epics, from [Dante](article.html?id=dante)'s *Divine Comedy* to [Shakespeare](article.html?id=shakespeare)'s sonnets and Milton's *Paradise Lost*, poetry has been the medium through which human beings express their deepest experiences of beauty, grief, love, and encounter with God — and the classical tradition has always placed the reading and writing of poetry at the heart of a truly human education.
:::

